The learning outcomes of private schools in Scotland have traditionally been good, and this success has also continued in 2018 as a result of good test results. Success has been boosted by individual and communal success in sport, art, music and other community projects.
These schools of more than 30,000 students across Scotland, represented by the Scottish Board of Private Schools SCIS, aim to provide a high level of service to their students and their parents.
Private schools strive to prepare their students for their chosen careers, graduate and higher education, as well as global citizenship.
As an educational operator who can design and implement customized study content, we have seen the role of languages as a popular and hoped-for subject in continuing educational institutions.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a person in a language he understands, the message goes to his head.
If you speak to a person in his own language, the message will go into his heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships with people from other countries.
From this year’s latest results, we can see that languages are at the top of the list in terms of penetration rates among private schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest grade A.
Based on the data collected from 74 schools in SCIS, 72 per cent of students who received the best grade A studied Mandarin Chinese, 72 per cent studied German, 69 per cent studied French, and 63 per cent studied Spanish.
This shows that private schools in Scotland support the study of foreign languages as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are currently optional subjects, but they are considered to be of the same value as natural sciences (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), both in the study programme of private schools and elsewhere.
According to a 2014 survey conducted by the UK Employment Office, 17% of situations where employers had difficulty finding a suitable employee for the job were explained by a lack of language skills.
The development of language skills is therefore even more necessary in order to promote the future career development of young people.
The more possible tasks require language skills, the more essential these skills become in the global world.
If a person has studied another language, he or she will have an advantage in the future from this lifelong skill, regardless of the career he or she has chosen.
The ability to communicate directly with a foreigner automatically puts a person with language skills ahead of the competition.
According to a 2013 survey by YouGovi, 75% of over 4,000 adults in the UK are unable to speak a foreign language, and French was the only language with a double-digit figure of 15%.
This is why investing in language teaching is important for today’s children.
In particular, the knowledge of the languages of developing countries gives children a better chance of finding a meaningful career.
Within Scotland, schools differ in what languages they teach.
Several schools focus on traditional languages, while some specifically teach languages that are supposed to be important for the British in 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese and Japanese.
Despite your child’s interests, private schools always have several language options taught by specialized teachers.
Scottish private schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future may bring.
At this time, it cannot be denied that languages in the international business environment will continue to be very important for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Today’s languages should indeed be seen as “international communication skills”.
Private schools will continue to offer this freedom of choice, diversity and high-level education to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the head of SCIS, the Scottish Board of Private Schools
