Harvard students complete a course to provide adequate rest guidance
This year, all undergraduate students at Harvard University will take part in a course designed to increase student rest. The course is a counterattack to the thriving macho culture at the university, where students will spend a long night working with the power of caffeine.
According to the researcher, students at the best university in the world are often quite unaware of the basics of their own well-being.
Designed by Charles Czeisler, a professor of medicine at Harvard University, who works on sleep research at Brigham and Women's Hospital, the course is believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
Czeisler got the idea for the course after he lectured on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“After the lecture, a young woman came to me and said, ‘Why am I only hearing about it now, in my last year of study?’
No one had ever told him about the need for a dream, which I thought was surprising,” he said in an interview with Telegraph.
For the first time this year, the course will guide students on how the right unit habits support academic and athletic performance and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, Professor of Medicine at Harvard University and Vice President of Health Services at the University, said the university ended up organizing the course after hearing how students suffered from serious sleep deprivation during the study week.
An hour-long course includes a set of interactive tasks.
In one section, students are presented with a picture of a dorm room where the student can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports equipment and books, thus gaining information about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of sleep deprivation on sports performance and the importance of regular evening activities.
In the second section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to reflect on their daily routines.
“We know that this has no immediate impact on students’ behavior.
We believe, however, that they have the right to know about these matters in exactly the same way as they have the right to know about the health effects of smoking,” adds Professor Czeisler.
According to Professor Czeisler, night-long study marathons are still a subject of pride, and the increasing pressures of modern technology and students made the sleep deficit a growing problem.
“Getting enough and quality sleep should be a ‘secret weapon’ for students against stress, fatigue and anxiety, and even weight gain, because sleep deprivation causes a state of starvation in the brain, which is why a person is constantly hungry,” the professor points out.
Raymond So, a Californian 19-year-old student of chemical and physical psychology, helped Professor Czeisler plan the course after attending one of the courses he taught for his first year at Harvard last year.
He says the course opened his eyes and gave an impetus to the organisation of a comprehensive course for all campus students.
He hopes that all doctoral students will be able to complete a similar course of study before moving to a competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm clock to remind them of bedtime in addition to waking up in the morning and to keep in mind the side effects caused by electronic display devices and LED lighting "blue light" for circadian rhythms, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
