The vaccine teaches the immune system to identify malignant cells as part of the treatment
In the method, resistant cells are isolated from the patient and modified in the laboratory
After treatment, cells injected back into the body are able to ‘see’ the typical proteins of multiple cancers
The study has shown promising results in patients with different cancers.
For example, cancer cells in a patient with ovarian cancer disappeared within 18 months after being treated with a vaccine that teaches the immune system to identify malignant cells.
In the method, resistant cells are isolated from the patient and modified in the laboratory in such a way that they are able to ‘see’ the HER2 proteins typical of multiple cancers.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, U.S.A., describes the method: “Based on our results, this is a very promising vaccine.”
HER2 "controls the growth of several types of cancer," Professor Berzofsky explains. "These include breast cancer, as well as ovarian, lung and colon cancers."
A similar approach – taking resistant cells from the patient and teaching them to attack cancer cells – has also produced results in the treatment of a type of leukaemia.
