Situation of red tide algae blooms: concentrations fall in the regions of Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to a recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there is a general decrease in the amount of algae in the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, more scattered algae areas are reported in the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, indicating a possible decrease in concentrations.
The Red tide algae bloom extends along the coast about 130 miles from Pinellas to the southern counties of Lee.
Ferries can be spotted ten miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but are less frequent than last week.
Red tide algae blooms have also been observed in Pasco County.
Moderate concentrations were reported from the coast of Pinellas County last week, concentrations ranged from low to high on the coasts of Hillsborough County, from background to high in the counties of Manatee and Sarasota, from background to moderate in Charlotte County and from background to high in the coasts of Lee County and from Collier County, respectively.
Respiratory symptoms are further reported in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
During the last week, there were no reports of respiratory symptoms in the north-west of Florida.
